  "local_port": 38970,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How is parfum/perfume made?",
  "response": "Perfume, also known as parfum, is a fragrant liquid made from essential oils, aroma compounds, and solvents. The process of making perfume involves several steps:\n\n1. **Extraction of Essential Oils:**\n   Essential oils are the backbone of perfume. They are extracted from various parts of plants, such as flowers, leaves, and roots, through several methods:\n   - **Distillation:** Steam is passed through plant material to vaporize the oils, which are then condensed and collected.\n   - **Expression:** Mechanical pressing is used to extract oils from citrus peels.\n   - **Enfleurage:** Flowers are placed on a layer of fat that absorbs their oils, which are later extracted with alcohol.\n   - **Solvent Extraction:** Plant materials are mixed with a solvent (usually hexane) to draw out the oils. The solvent is then evaporated, leaving behind a concentrated oil called an absolute.\n\n2. **Blending:**\n   Once the essential oils are extracted, they are blended together by a perfumer (also known as a \"nose\") to create a specific fragrance. This process involves mixing various essential oils, aroma compounds, and sometimes synthetic ingredients to achieve the desired scent. The blend is carefully adjusted to ensure the fragrance has the right balance of top, middle, and base notes.\n\n3. **Aging:**\n   The blended mixture is allowed to age for several weeks or months. This aging process allows the different components to meld together and develop a more harmonious scent.\n\n4. **Filtering:**\n   After aging, the perfume is filtered to remove any impurities or particles that may have formed during the aging process.\n\n5. **Dilution:**\n   The concentrated perfume oil is then diluted with a solvent, usually ethanol, to achieve the desired strength. The concentration of the perfume oil in the final product determines the type of fragrance:\n   - **Parfum (Extrait):** 20-30% perfume oil\n   - **Eau de Parfum:** 15-20% perfume oil\n   - **Eau de Toilette:** 5-15% perfume oil\n   - **Eau de Cologne:** 2-5% perfume oil\n   - **Eau Fra\u00eeche:** 1-3% perfume oil\n\n6. **Bottling:**\n   The final step is bottling the perfume. It is carefully poured into bottles, which are then sealed and labeled.\n\nEach step in the process requires precision and expertise to ensure the final product is of high quality and has a pleasing scent.",
